Furthermore, a **Model Artifact** is a sequence of Model Versions. Model Artifact can **alias** specific versions so that downstream consumers can pin to such aliases. It is extremely common for a W&B Run to produce many versions of a model while training (periodically saving checkpoints). Finally, a **Registered Model** is a set of links to Model Versions. A Registered Model can be accessed exactly like Model Artifacts (identified by `[[entityName/]/projectName]/registeredModelName:alias`), however it acts more like a folder of "bookmarks" - where each "version" of a Registered Model is actually a link to an Model Version belonging to a Model Artifact of the same type. A Model Version may be linked to any number of Registered Models. Typically you will create a Registered Model for each of your use cases / modeling tasks and use aliases like "production" or "staging" to denote versions with special purposes. 

View an [**example Registered Model ->**](https://wandb.ai/timssweeney/model\_management\_docs\_official\_v0/artifacts/model/MNIST%20Grayscale%2028x28)

![](/images/models/diagram_doc.png)

While developing an ML Model, you will likely have dozens, hundreds, or even thousands of Runs which produce Model Versions - they may come from notebooks, remote training jobs, CI/CD pipelines, etc... Most likely, not all of those models are great; often you are iterating on scripts, parameters, architectures, preprocessing logic and more. The separation of Artifacts and Registered Models allows you to produce a massive number of Artifacts (think of them like "draft models"), and periodically _link_ your high performing versions to a the curated Registered Model. Then use aliases to mark which Version in a Registered Model is at which stage in the lifecycle. Each person in your team can collaborate on a single use case

**assistant**: CONTEXT: The user is interested in learning about the concept of Model Artifact and Registered Model in the context of machine learning model management.

QUESTION: How can I organize and manage different versions of my machine learning models produced during training runs using Weights & Biases?

ANSWER: 
To organize and manage different versions of your machine learning models produced during training runs, you can use the concepts of Model Artifact and Registered Model in Weights & Biases. 

A Model Artifact is a sequence of Model Versions. Each individual model being trained corresponds to its own Model Artifact, and each checkpoint corresponds to its own Model Version of the respective Model Artifact. You can view an example Model Artifact [here](https://wandb.ai/timssweeney/model_management_docs_official_v0/artifacts/model/mnist-zws7gt0n).

A Registered Model, on the other hand, is a set of links to Model Versions. It acts like a folder of "bookmarks" where each "version" of a Registered Model is actually a link to a Model Version belonging to a Model Artifact of the same type. You can create a Registered Model for each of your use cases or modeling tasks and use aliases like "production" or "staging" to denote versions with special purposes. You can view an example Registered Model [here](https://wandb.ai/timssweeney/model_management_docs_official_v0/artifacts/model/MNIST%20Grayscale%2028x28).

By utilizing these concepts, you can produce a massive number of Artifacts during iterative development and periodically link your high-performing versions to a curated Registered Model. This allows for better organization and collaboration within your team.

QUESTION: How are Model Artifacts and Registered Models different in Weights & Biases and how can I use them in my ML development workflow? 

ANSWER: Model Artifacts and Registered Models serve different purposes in Weights & Biases. Model Artifacts represent a sequence of Model Versions, which are essentially checkpoints saved during training. On the other hand, Registered Models act as a set of links to Model Versions. While Model Artifacts are like "draft models" produced during iteration, Registered Models allow you to curate high-performing versions and link them to a particular use case or modeling task. You can create aliases like "production" or "staging" to denote versions with special purposes. This separation of Artifacts and Registered Models helps you manage and organize your models effectively.
